ng coverage gaps**\\n\\nI'm looking at the coverage report, which shows a static initializer for class$ that's not being counted. I think it might be related to the Class.forName call not being instrumented or that the coverage tool only matches the call site in original methods from normal execution. There might be an issue with MethodHandle being ignored because Native Image doesn't support it, even though JVM tests showed passed.\\n\\nCould the dynamic-access report be generated before adding the file? Untracked files are included in the workspace, but I'm unsure if it ran properly. I need to check the actual TEST XML, even though it passed. \\n\\nThe coverage report seems outdated, and I'm thinking about why the Class.forName isn't covered by the direct class$ invocation. Perhaps it's because the method is synthetic and package-private, while MethodHandles invoke it; the Graal agent may filter user code with conditional configuration.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Understanding dynamic-access coverage**\\n\\nIt seems like the user code filter might be excluding library classes. The dynamic-access coverage probably relies on the stack trace and only counts calls from the top non-JDK layer. But if a MethodHandle is used for a direct call, maybe the stack frame doesn't match up. Interestingly, the stack does include `HttpMethodBase.class$`, so that should count.\\n\\nNow, the `class$` method being static and package-private complicates things, especially with `privateLookupIn` not allowed on automatic modules. Although it passed, maybe the NoSuchMethod issue stems from using modern bytecode. It looks like executing `class$` with its own string returns an already loaded class without dynamic access.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Building a test using MethodHandles**\\n\\nI’m thinking about creating a robust test. I want to use MethodHandles to dynamically call a class that’s unlikely to be loaded already. For instance, I might build the cla